HOUSE RESOLUTION NO. 35
BY REPRESENTATIVE WALTERS
CONDOLENCES: Expresses the condolences of the House of Representatives on the death
of Bernard LaFayette, Jr.
1 A RESOLUTION
2 To express the condolences of the House of Representatives on the death of Bernard
3 LaFayette, Jr.
4 WHEREAS, it is with immense sadness and profound regret that the House of
5 Representatives of the Legislature of Louisiana has learned of the passing of Bernard
6 LaFayette, Jr.; and
7 WHEREAS, Bernard LaFayette, Jr., was born on July 29, 1940, in Tampa, Florida,
8 and grew up in Tampa and Philadelphia, Pennsylvania; and
9 WHEREAS, Dr. LaFayette was a student at the American Baptist Theological
10 Seminary during the Freedom Rides of 1961 and served as a leader in both the Nashville
11 Student Movement and the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee; and
12 WHEREAS, Dr. LaFayette was one of twenty-one student Freedom Riders who were
13 attacked during a demonstration at the Montgomery Greyhound Bus Station on May 20,
14 1961; after the attack, he traveled to Jackson, Mississippi, where he was arrested on a
15 breach-of-the-peace charge and spent nearly forty days in Parchman Prison; and
16 WHEREAS, after his release from prison, Dr. LaFayette remained in Jackson to
17 recruit new Freedom Riders and organize the Jackson Nonviolent Movement; he later joined
18 the staff of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference (SCLC) and worked on numerous
19 campaigns, including Selma, from 1963 to 1965; and
20 WHEREAS, Dr. LaFayette served as the national coordinator for the Poor People's
21 Campaign in 1968; during his final conversation with Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr., he was
